---

<Layout
  title="Hybrid inverter or grid-tied inverter? | Taqinor"
  description="Deye hybrid inverter (with storage, service continuity) or Huawei SUN2000 grid-tied inverter (self-consumption without a battery): how the choice is made, explained simply."
  ogSlug="equipement"
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(jsonLd)} />
  <div class="v2">
    <V2Enhance />
    <Article33Ribbon />

    <Breadcrumb items={[{ label: 'Home', href: L('/') }, { label: 'Guides', href: L('/guides') }, { label: 'Hybrid or grid-tied inverter?' }]} />

    <article class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 pb-24 pt-12 sm:pb-28">
      <p class="tech-label v2-kicker rule-brass text-brass-300">Guide · Equipment</p>
      <h1 class="display v2-page-title mt-5 text-white">Hybrid inverter or grid-tied inverter?</h1>
      <p class="v2-lead mt-6 text-lune-soft">
        The inverter is the part that converts the direct current from the panels into current you
        can use at home: without it, nothing works. The debate between
        <strong class="text-lune">hybrid</strong> and <strong class="text-lune">grid-tied</strong>
        may seem technical, but it comes down to a single question: do you store the energy, yes or
        no?
      </p>

      <h2 class="display v2-section-title mt-12 text-white">The hybrid inverter (Deye)</h2>
      <p class="v2-lead mt-5 text-lune-soft">
        The hybrid is the inverter that knows how to manage a battery. The Deye units (single-phase
        and three-phase, from 5 to 30 kW) drive the panels and the storage at once, with built-in
        CAN BMS management. Their appeal is twofold: shifting energy from the day to the evening, and
        switching to standalone mode within a few milliseconds during an outage — something a
        grid-tied inverter never does (for safety, it disconnects automatically the moment the grid
        drops). That versatility has a cost — you have to add the battery itself — and a storage
        inverter converts energy with one more step than a plain grid-coupling inverter.
      </p>

      <h2 class="display v2-section-title mt-12 text-white">The grid-tied inverter (Huawei SUN2000)</h2>
      <p class="v2-lead mt-5 text-lune-soft">
        The grid-tied inverter does one thing, but does it very well: send solar production to your
        appliances and the grid, with no storage to amortise. The Huawei SUN2000 units (string type)
        are built for this direct self-consumption, from homes to commercial rooftops. Less hardware,
        fewer conversions, fewer things that can fail: it's the simplest, most efficient solution as
        long as your consumption follows the sun. The downside is well known — no back-up during an
        outage, and nothing to offer in the evening beyond what the panels produce in that instant.
      </p>

      <h2 class="display v2-section-title mt-12 text-white">Why Law 82-21 tips the balance</h2>
      <p class="v2-lead mt-5 text-lune-soft">
        You might think a grid-tied inverter "makes up for it" by selling back all its surplus. Law
        82-21 says the opposite. Injection is capped at 20% of your annual production, and that
        surplus is bought back at only 0.18 to 0.21 DH/kWh — whereas you buy that same kWh from the
        grid at between 0.90 and 1.66 DH/kWh. In other words, the energy you do not consume on site
        is worth little. That reinforces the logic of both inverters: on a daytime profile, the
        grid-tied unit already captures most of that value through direct self-consumption; on an
        evening profile, it's the hybrid that recovers what exporting would barely pay for, by
        shifting it into your peak hours.
      </p>

      <h2 class="display v2-section-title mt-12 text-white">How we choose</h2>
      <p class="v2-lead mt-5 text-lune-soft">
        The choice of inverter is therefore not the first, it's the last: it follows from the
        decision on storage, which itself follows from your consumption profile and the stability of
        your grid. We work back up the chain in the right order — your bill and your consumption
        hours first, the hardware after — instead of starting from a model decided in advance.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-10 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        <a href={L('/guides/faut-il-des-batteries')} class="border border-white/40 px-5 py-3 text-sm font-bold text-white transition-colors hover:border-white hover:bg-white/10">Do you need batteries? →</a>
        <a href={L('/équipement')} class="border border-white/40 px-5 py-3 text-sm font-bold text-white transition-colors hover:border-white hover:bg-white/10">See the equipment →</a>
        <a href={L('/guides')} class="border border-white/40 px-5 py-3 text-sm font-bold text-white transition-colors hover:border-white hover:bg-white/10">All the guides →</a>
      </div>
    </article>

    <CtaBand title="We settle hybrid or grid-tied in the study — and it's free." href={L('/contact') + '#simulateur'} />

    <StickyCta />
  </div>
</Layout>
